element_texts.text:
Dunbarton, May 29, 1856
Dearest Isaac,
If you come this week you will not receive a letter if I write but something may detain you.  Yours came by  Tuesday's mail.  I looked for it Saturday but not very confidently.  I am so glad Margo does so well and does not trouble you very much - but now I want to see him.  Glad you had a pleasant journey, and found dear Lucy no worse.  Really glad the cape will be of use - I feared it would not answer for a city boy.  Hope Jon will get Lucy's garden in fine order and not be a very great while about it.  I am willing to spare you a little while but I do not love to think of your going West again.  A letter came from Mr. Keyes Tuesday.  In it such woeful chirography that I have no patience to decipher it all

There is considerable DU Quoin news in it.  Sen. Grose is East assisting Miss Paine.  The babies have really had a harsh time with Diarrhea - both of them but both seem better now.  Willie has very genefatibly lost flesh - one night he did not really get to sleep till after two o'clock.  I would think he was asleep and just get nicely covered and unclear for a snoose myself when he would cry.  He cried about two hours very hard indeed.  I could do nothing to still him.  Wilder? sleeps finally all the night.  I cannot leave him on the bed an instant awake without watching  - he creeps to the very edge as Margo used to and looks over without Margo's carefulness.  I could put on short dresses now - we have enough ready to begin with but this weather is too cold for the change. I keep thinking what a fine time you are all having together and am glad for you and it creeps into my mind now and then that I should have a nice time too if I

were there.  Cousin Samuel is here and does our running to Post Office, Store, etc.  A very quiet pleasant accommodating boy.  I've got a carriage for babies from Concord? at $2,00 with permission to take it back when done using.  They enjoy it very much.  I can put both into it but its too heavy then for me to  draw a great distance - so I take one when the other sleeps.  Everything is so beautiful here now, such a unclear bright lively green, that I do wish Mother and Anna could see it.  We did not have one bright fine day while they were here.  Ive great love to them and to all from me.  Thank Mother and Anna for the few lines from them, and tell Anna I shall be glad of the long letter whenever she can write.  Mother is well as usual and sleeps better than before for a long time - thinks it must be because she gets the babies to sleep every day.  I shall hope the maill

of today will bring me another letter from you.
Lovingly, your own Nettie
Have had asparagus twice.  The tomatoes seem no larger than when we set them out.  The cold weather delays them.  Corner of garden not planted yet.  We heard indirectly yesterday that Jenny was succeeding very well in her new employ.  You did not say a word about Perci.  I want to hear from him.
Antoinette Dunbarton
May 29 '56
Bangor
